Auture Systems Statement on AppSys21 Future

When we started development on AppSys21 a few months ago our vision was to offer a free, easy to use, discord-only application bot as an alternative to overcomplicated bots, payed bots or websites like google forms.
Now a few months later, were running well and on track. Updates are coming at a slower pace but we do indeed have new features in the pipeline and are working on quite some more to come. But were also facing several challenges which are demotivating to the point that, at least I (AFK_Pilot), sometimes would like to throw it all in the corner, stop my server and leave it as it is. Thus, heres an old fashioned status update like in the FlSys21 times, just 10x bigger.

Verification

As most may have noticed, weve disabled invitations for AppSys21. This is to keep it from joining over 100 servers which would worst case ban it from API requests or best case simply disable invites by itself.
This is because to have your bot join more than 100 servers, bot verification is required.
Verification is straight forward: You answer a few questions on functionality of your bot, data handling and collection as well as security and hosting/infrastructure in a form on the discord developer portal. Oh and you are required to do facial verification. yes.
As someone who has never shared their face on discord and keeps a lot of other private details - uh well - private, I am seriously reluctant to have my governmental ID sent to a third party company so they can do identity verification.
Dont get me wrong, verification is a good idea. It brings the community onwards with committed developers bots being clearly marked and the data security questions in the form make you implement a lot of helpful features considering data handling into your bot. Still, requiring someone to send their ID to a company to do facial verification for an automated discord user? No thanks. But the problems dont just stop there: Lets pretend I have already had identity verification and AppSys21 also got through the bot verification process. Now the next problem awaits us which brings us to the next section:

Privileged Gateway Intents

Maintaining a stateful application can be difficult when it comes to the amount of data you're expected to process, especially at scale. Gateway Intents are a system to help you lower that computational burden. Some of these gateway intents are defined as Privileged due to the sensitive nature of the data they grant, and access can be enabled below. - Discord, description of gateway intents as found in the bot verification form.
You can imagine a gateway intent as some sort of door: If you have an intent enabled the door is open and your request can get to discord. If you dont have an intent enabled, the request will be denied.
Privileged Gateway Intents are those that grant you access to presence and more importantly, members/users (so user ID and stuff which is, as you know, a big part of AppSys21 workflow). Right now, we can simply enable them, after verification though we will need to apply for them. And if the application is rejected, AppSys21 is useless. The real problem with intents is only coming in the future though, which brings us the next thing.

Slash Commands, Interactions and Message Content Intent

Discord has started introducing new ways to interact with bots called interactions. Im sure youve seen them at least somewhere: Slash commands, buttons, dropdown menus and probably there are more to come. Slash commands and interactions are cool, not even lying. It helps users get the commands right and if I look at how many errors we get everyday, oh dear would I love to provide some extra help. Now though, discord has announced a new privileged gateway intent to be introduced in April 2022: Message content. Basically, if you dont have it, your bot is no longer able to interact with message content, except in DMs and a few other cases. And of course, in a very understandable way this makes sense: Until now, a bot couldve simply recorded all your messages in #general or literally any other channel it has access to and saved them in a document.
So if you dont have this privileged gateway intent, you will only be able to use interactions (slash commands, buttons, dropdown menus) as communication methods with your bot.
As confirmed by discord staff, wanting to use the old command system or wanting to make commands without slash commands is not a valid reason for getting the intent, thus, AppSys21 would most probably be forced into slash command interactions.
Now you can imagine this a bit like if you were to learn French for the memes or whatever and then in school youre suddenly forced to learn French every 2nd day and learn your vocabulary. Not saying discords interactions are a meme here, but I guess you get the point: its a pain in the ass. Also, slash commands are much more limited than the, for now still regular, chat commands.
I wouldnt know how to implement the functionality of MassBanTool in a slash command for example The functional limits of slash commands arent the only problem here though, discord.py is missing implementation of it completely. What is discord.py? Let me explain.

Discord.py

Discord.py is the API wrapper that were using. Its complicated stuff but essentially its a collection of functions and files that make communication with discord very easy. So instead of having to work with the official API (complicated, long, not that efficient tbh) in our own code and stuff, we just provide discord.py with some arguments and it sends these arguments into the code that then communicates with discord. I mean thats kinda how it works. Very easy explanation, dont blame me thx <3
But now that I have kinda introduced discord.py to you, its already time to scrub it all again

Rapptz/Danny says bye

Now this time recently actually means a few hours ago (on 28th of august). Danny/Rapptz, the main (or rather sole) developer of discord.py has recently announced his step-down and that no one was found to further continue the development of discord.py. As written in his step-down gist the Development will cease and the repository will be put into a read-only mode.
Why did he cease development? Well short form is the way Discord is going with bots. He states his [] motivation to work on Discord has been dwindling over the past year, since the verification system was introduced. Persistent tone deafness, deadlines, lies, gaslighting, and rapid changes without proper consultation by the Discord employees make it hard to have the motivation necessary to work with the frequent changes and the limitations being placed on me.
What does this mean for AppSys21? Well our API wrapper will no longer receive updates. It doesnt have and will never get the implementation of slash commands and will also not get any new features to keep up with new Discord sided bot features.
This leaves us with the following options:
- stop development of all our bots (yes all our bots, MassBanTool too)
- keep using discord.py until it is completely incompatible with Discord and until we get limited to slash command interactions in April 2022
- use another API wrapper which would lead to us having to rewrite all of our code except for the core algorithms
- use another API wrapper and another coding language so wed need to rewrite our code from the ground up and also learn new coding languages

So what now?

Discord is forcing us through so much changes and adaptions to meet their requirements and guidelines its just demotivating. We havent yet made a decision as a development team on what well do about it, but for our users this means the possible discontinuation of AppSys21. We can guarantee that, if there are any, updates will be at a slower pace and the first ones would be filled with under the hood stuff and very few to no features at all.
I am very annoyed by this, especially since I understand that (except for facial identity verification) this is a step in the right direction. Its not the right thing slash commands and interactions limit the possibilities, but its a step towards user privacy, safety and easier usability which I, and every other bot developer too, should appreciate. What annoys me about it is the incredible amount of work we need to put in to ensure the functionality of AppSys21. Of course, April 2022 is in the far future right now, but were only a team of a few young developers who work on this project in their free time, we have lots of other stuff to do. We already had to do a lot for ensuring wed get through verification if I was to decide to do identity verification, but now with the added challenge of an entire rewrite the demotivation is as high as never before. Sincerely,
-AFK_Pilot
